               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t18320405-239-victim2047" type="victimName">MARY WOOLRIDGE<interp inst="t18320405-239-victim2047" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            . I am the wife of Robert Oram Woolridge, an <rs id="t18320405-239-viclabel1409" type="occupation">ironmonger</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-239-victim2045 t18320405-239-viclabel1409"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-239-victim2047 t18320405-239-viclabel1409"></join>, who lives in Whitecross-street. On the 21st of March I was near <placeName id="t18320405-239-crimeloc1410">Chiswell-street, Finsbury</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-239-crimeloc1410" type="placeName" value="Chiswell-street, Finsbury"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-239-crimeloc1410" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-239-off1406 t18320405-239-crimeloc1410"></join>, between one and two o'clock - I was standing on the pavement, and thought of going across the road, but there was a great crowd; I had a pocket-book in my pocket, containing the duplicates of the property stated; a person told me I had had my pocket picked - I went to the station, and found the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-239-person2048">
                  ROBERT 
                  ROBERTSON
               <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2048" type="surname" value="ROBERTSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2048" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2048" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable A 63.) I was on duty, and saw the prosecutrix and some persons about<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183204050102"></xptr>her; I saw the prisoner lift her gown up, and put his two fore fingers into her pocket, and take out this pocket-book - I grasped at him, but he got from me; I ran after him, and took him with the book in his left-hand pocket - I met with great resistance, and could not have taken him if my brother officer had not come up; about three hundred persons attacked us, and I was almost knocked stupid before I got to the station-house - the prisoner bit a piece out of my hand.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-239-person2049">
                  WILLIAM 
                  SHEPHERD
               <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2049" type="surname" value="SHEPHERD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2049" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-239-person2049" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I assisted in taking the prisoner - I saw him run across the road, and the officer after him; I saw him passing the book from one pocket to the other - I seized him by one arm, and he threw it down; we were opposed by a great number of persons, and were attacked with sticks, stones, and mud.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I heard there were two waggons of victuals to be given away, but there was no such thing; I was going home, and saw this old pocket-book - I took it up, and some gentlemen cried out Stop-thief! they came and took me; two or three people said I had picked it up- I said I would go any where; I went to the station, and they asked what I had been doing, and they went round among the people and found this lady.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320405-239-verdict1411" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18320405-239-verdict1411" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
